%p
  Recently at work I have been using a Kanban board with a fellow designer to manage our design work.

%p
  Although early days, we have found it to be a real help and it has garnered some interest beyond the project we are on.

%p We started the board with the following goals:

%ul
  %li Track what each other is working on
  %li Record our design reviews and comments
  %li Better develop our design process (using hypotheses)
  %li Record design decisions and evidence for them
  %li Show our process to the rest of the project
  %li Be able to (visually) organise and  priortise design work
  %li Involve our Product Owner in priortising what design work was being focused on

%p Even if you are the sole designer/UX person, it is valuable to be able to communicate with other people on a project what you are working on and your current priorities.

%p The board has helped us structure our work and track it better, as well as expose that workflow to other members of the team.

%p It has also shown us where our design bottlenecks are, and what things we need to swarm on together to speed up and get done.

%p It takes discipline to maintain but provides real value if you do.

%h2#so_what_is_kanban So, what is Kanban?

%p
  If you've worked on a software project before, you may have encountered
  %a{:href => "https://www.atlassian.com/agile/kanban"}Kanban boards.

%p On a Kanban board, items (jobs, tasks or anything) are written on cards which sit on a board in a set of columns. Each column has a label indicating the cards status or activity. The cards move across the board as they change status.

%p The simplest Kanban boards are structured in three columns of "todo", "doing", "done". Often this board structure then evolves with a "backlog" or "ideas" column preceeding the todo column for ideas to be stored.

%div.todo-board
  %div
    %h3.h4.title
      Ideas
  %div
    %h3.h4.title
      Todo
  %div
    %h3.h4.title
      Doing
  %div
    %h3.h4.title
      Done

%p Like many workflows ours didn't feel like it fit with this simplisitic structure. But we did feel like this technique could help us structure our work.

%h2#how_we_implemented_kanban How we implemented Kanban

%p The first step we took was to sketch out the phases a bit of design work would go through.

%p I had a collection of scribbled notes on our design process written on the train.  We collected those together and tried to get some general agreed phases.

%p To test if it would work we realised we needed to get this on a whiteboard.

%p We found some whiteboard space (a precious commodity) and started to draw our board up.

%p
  We both knew this was going to be a long journey. There was also a risk of exposing our work too early and receiving too much input too soon. It's better to get something up and public. The risk was worth the reward.

%h3 First implementation

%p After going backwards and forwards over the column names, we sketched out our board and added some cards.

%p IMAGE

%p The idea behind the columns where:

%ol{:id => "first-implementation"}
  %li
    %h4 Backlog
    %p The is where our ideas live. Design hypotheses. Components to look into and explore. Things to optimise. Bugs or "That's not great is its".
  %li
    %h4 Elaborate
    %p The phase where we are actively working on a problem, but exploring the shape and size of it. Looking at current solutions and the reasons they exist, as well as other people's.

  %li
    %h4 Refine
    %p Here we are refining our ideas into testable chunks of work. Sketching paper prototypes. Thinking how a problem might be solved but an iterative area of work.
  %li
    %h4 Build
    %p The stage where we formally think an idea is worth pursuing. We have a hypothesis, we have refined it and now want to build something formally to test and review
  %li
    %h4 Review
    %p Formal review time. Either with a fellow designer or a member of the product team (or programme or beyond).
  %li
    %h4 Test/Evaluate
    %p Time to get it in front of people and work out if it has the desired outcomes.
  %li
    %h4 Done
    %p All work finished. Idea explored, built, reviewed, tested with users.

%p We got something up. And the second we did we saw what we felt was right, but also what we felt was missing.

%p We didn't know where and by whom something was reviewed. Nor did we get a good sense of what was bouncing around after review.

%p We also wanted to ensure our process was repeatable. Repeating high value things like documenting design decisions. We wanted to have that explicit, rather than implicit.

%p As designers we're part of the board and ceremonies for the development team. Our work feeds into the Scrum/Kanban flow of the development board, but we help with frontend tickets too.

%p It was clear immediately that the development board of the project we were on had informed us.

%p We had copied some of the naming conventions and flow. It felt like it captured some of what we wanted to do, but not enough.

%h3 Exposing the workflow

%p We had started using the board. As we used it and explained it, it felt like there needed to be an iterative pattern or process in the middle.

%p In hindsight, this is where we got a little too complicated early on. We knew we would see real value in exposing the iterative nature of our work. We struggled to find that balance.

%p
  Having looked for other examples of designers using Kanban, I stumbled across
  = succeed "." do
    %a{:href => "/"}this blog post about Kanban
  It explained how Conceptboard had used it.

%p I thought the Z-shaped pattern quite interesting.  It showed the iterative pattern of a design artefact going through rounds of review and refinement.

%p Inspired by this, we created a less-conventional Kanban design that looked like the below:

