%p The idea behind this structure is that important sub-phases of design are exposed. The flow of a card on this board is still left to right but if a card merited it, it could fall through additional phases.

%p
  A card that goes through review would jump from
  %strong Design - Prototype
  to
  %strong Review - Design
  moving after that again into the
  %strong Design
  column but this time in the
  %strong Refine
  cell.

%p Cards would now move through a Z-shape or in a circular fashion. Their iterative journey surfaced.

%p Our second feature was the drawing out of what wanted to make sure we did with each bit of design work. The process of documenting and sharing our work and then getting it in a product (prototype or production).

%p Looking at this now it is easy for us to see the faults.  At the time we were so close to it, it took us time to step back and see what was working and what wasn't.

%p
  We sacrificed the simplicity of our board to expose the iterative flow. We had completely messed up any notion of done by filling things in that column rather.

%h3 Wider feedback

%p I now felt ready to ask for some feedback.

%p I grabbed an experienced service designer I knew and walked him through the board.

%p It was great to hear he loved what we were doing. He also poked and prodded the thinking behind everything.

%p
  Taking the time to explain your concept is often the quickest way to expose the holes in your thinking. This is because you have to explain your idea without your hidden assumptions and background knowledge.

%p
  The complicated nature of the flow was clear.  Not in the fact that the designer couldn't understand and appreciate the flow, but that he was completely unsure of how it would work by looking at it.

%p Another interesting point the service designer made was about our prioritisation of cards.

%p
  I mentioned that we wanted to have a sense of what was more important. Our idea was to rank cards and show that on the board with high priority cards being at the top of the
