%p We now had a stronger structure for our cards.

%p At this stage, it felt like an optimisation too far to use coloured cards. We knew there was value to that system of categorisation. But it felt like a premature optimisation.

%p We also had plenty of space left on the card to add things like tags, avatars and Jira numbers. And plenty of time to have finer grained categories too, further down the line.

%h3 Simplifying it

%p The board now felt like it was adding value. The cards were now easier to understand and the board was explicit at which stage our work was.

%p The development team we sit in has a very experienced Scrum Master. I felt the board and my ability to explain it was now at a point where I could expose it further and to more rigorous examination.

%p We grabbed some time and took them through the board.

%p The board received more love. But the Scrum Master also noted two things they would change:

%ul
  %li The board column structure was too hard to understand at first glance
  %li We didn't really have a real done column

%p It would have been easy to argue with the Scrum Master and say that an iterative process cannot be displayed in a linear fashion.

%p However, this was the third or fourth time we had heard something similar about the visual structure. Every time we explained it, people understood it. But we wanted this board to expose something about how we worked to our project and the wider organisation.

%p Asking the Scrum Master about other ways of displaying iterations he mentioned the use of sticky dots.

%p This idea seemed like a very neat way of indicating what had been reviewed and by whom.

%p Taking this opportunity we went back to basics. We explained our work flow and design process to the Scrum Master who scribbled on the board as we did.

